                    "ref_id": "TABREF2"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Biomass Production"
        },
        {
            "text": "The gain in the content of glycyrrhizic acid and liq uiritin in the roots under 60-70% WC had the highest (89.4 and 124.6%, respectively), followed by the mod erate treatment (40.0 and 61.3%, respectively) as com pared to the control plants. There was no significant difference between the strong WC treatment and con trol (Figs. 1a, 1b) . At 60-70% WC, the amounts of glycyrrhizic acid and liquiritin in plant roots were the highest among the studied four levels of soil water con ditions: the gain increased by 85.0 and 119.4%, respectively (Figs. 1c, 1d) . At the lowest WC, glycyr rhizic acid amount in plant roots decreased, although no difference in liquiritin amount between these and control plants was found (Figs. 1c, 1d ).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 323,
                    "end": 337,
                    "text": "(Figs. 1a, 1b)",
                    "ref_id": null
                },
                {
                    "start": 543,
                    "end": 557,
                    "text": "(Figs. 1c, 1d)",
